e most momentous that Jefferson receives while president, appears in the National Intelligencer the following day. Having received congressional approval to send an expedition to locate a continental route to the Pacific, Jefferson drafts instructions and a cipher for Meriwether Lewis and arranges for the needed instruments. Following through on a promise to a friend to give his views of Christianity, Jefferson puts his religious creed on paper, a "Syllabus" of the morals of Jesus and the comparative merits of Christianity. He intends it only for a few trusted friends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh1 aOberg, Barbara B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691184876zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691184876423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691184876/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles